    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-11-03T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-11-03T02:00:00-05:00" n="433"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d433">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/7647: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-11-03T14:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 3, 1942—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 4—1:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1271. TF–71. To Secretary of Treasury from Adler. Re 1 of TF–63 of October
                        8.<note n="93" xml:id="d433fn93">Telegram No. 1147, October 8, 9 a.m., <ref
                            target="#pg_539">p. 539</ref>.</note> At Dr. Kung’s suggestion, board
                    has requested General Secretary and myself to make a trip to northwest to
                    investigate possibility of Board’s opening an [office at] Lanchow which would
                    grant United States dollar cover for commercial imports from Russia. General
                    Secretary and I [are] leaving for Lanchow November 3 for about 2 weeks.
                    [Adler.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
